'''Bangladesh Industrial and Technical Assistance Center''' is an autonomous government body and research center that researches ways to improve industrial production and provide technical knowledge and is located in [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=RFL employs 120 women trained by BITAC|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/business/rfl-employs-120-women-trained-bitac-1224070|accessdate=13 December 2017|work=The Daily Star|date=15 May 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh to export car parts|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-117504|accessdate=13 December 2017|work=The Daily Star|date=12 December 2009|language=en}}</ref> It is part of a Bangladesh government strategy to support Small Middle Enterprise.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dept|first1=International Monetary Fund Asia and Pacific|title=Bangladesh: Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper|date=2013|publisher=International Monetary Fund|isbn=9781475543520|page=120|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LmqM8I_8nH0C&pg=RA1-PA120&lpg=RA1-PA120&dq=Bangladesh+Industrial+and+Technical+Assistance+Center&source=bl&ots=ivgpGMJuZ4&sig=Rhdw4BUJMctr3x0OMh-RWOkf-jg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiOnauUtobYAhWRSN8KHWCOAUMQ6AEIzgEwEw#v=onepage&q=Bangladesh%20Industrial%20and%20Technical%20Assistance%20Center&f=false|language=en}}</ref>
==History== Bangladesh Industrial and Technical Assistance Center traces its origins to the Pakistan Industrial Technical Centre which was established through the merger of IRDC & PIPS in 1962. After the [[Independence of Bangladesh]] it was changed to Bangladesh Industrial and Technical Assistance Center.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bangladesh Industrial and Technical Assistance Center (BITAC)-Government of the People's Republic of Bangladesh|url=http://www.bitac.gov.bd/site/page/615d83a5-066b-43da-8642-898b92e3b66f/%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%9F%E0%A6%AD%E0%A7%82%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BF|website=bitac.gov.bd|accessdate=13 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>
