{{nihongo|'''Shōzō Murata'''|村田 省蔵|Murata Shōzō|extra=6 September 1878 – 15 March 1957}} was a Japanese entrepreneur, cabinet minister and diplomat before, during and after [[World War II]].

==Biography==
Murata was a native of [[Tokyo]] and a graduate of the Tokyo Higher Commerce School (now [[Hitotsubashi University]]). After graduation, he went to work with the ''Osaka Shosen Kaisha'' (currently [[Mitsui O.S.K. Lines]]), and transformed the relatively small company into a major [[shipping company]]. He was sent to the company’s branch in Shanghai in 1901 at the age of 24.<ref>{{cite book | last = Duus | first = Peter | year = 2013 | title = The Japanese Informal Empire in China, 1895-1937| publisher = Princeton University Press | isbn = 1400847931 }} page 43</ref> and eventually rose to the position of company president from 1934-1940.  In 1937, in response to increasing demands from the Japanese military for resources from the Japanese merchant fleet, Murata organized an {{nihongo|Autonomous Shipping Control Group|海運自治連盟|Kaiun Jichi Renmei}}, of which he served as chairman, to reduce competition and coordinate efforts between the seven largest shipping companies and the government.<ref>{{cite book | last = Chida | first = Tomohei | year = 2013 | title = The Japanese Shipping and Shipbuilding Industries: A History of their Modern Growth| publisher = Bloomsbury | isbn = 9781780939186}} page 53</ref>

In 1939, Murata was appointed to the [[House of Peers (Japan)|House of Peers]] in the [[Diet of Japan]]. Murata was representative of successful private entrepreneurs who were invited to join the ''[[Taisei Yokusankai]]'' political organization created by [[Fumimaro Konoe]] and his followers, and took active participation in debate on the [[state socialist]] [[controlled economy]] created under the [[National Mobilization Law]].

Murata was invited to become both [[Ministry of Communications (Japan)|Minister of Communications]] and [[Japanese Government Railway|Minister of Railways]] under the 3rd and 4th [[Fumimaro Konoe|Konoe administration]]s from 1940. In 1943, Murata became Japanese ambassador to the [[Second Philippine Republic]], and special advisor to the [[Japanese Fourteenth Area Army]] of the [[Imperial Japanese Army]]. As ambassador he brought a team of scholars from Japan to make a research report with recommendations  for the collaborationist government, told Present [[José P. Laurel|José Laurel]] that the Philippines had the right to make more demands upon the Japanese government; however, his report and efforts were ignored by the Japanese military.<ref>{{cite book | last = Friend | first = Theodore | year = 2014 | title = The Blue-Eyed Enemy: Japan Against the West in Java and Luzon, 1942-1945|publisher = Princeton University Press | isbn = 1400859468}} page 60, 67</ref> He was recalled to Japan in 1945.

In 1946, along with all members of the wartime Japanese government, Murata [[Purge (During Occupation of Japan)|purged from public office]] and was taken into custody by the [[Supreme Commander of the Allied Powers|American occupation authorities]] and held at [[Sugamo Prison]], where he was to be charged for [[war crimes]].<ref>http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27925201</ref> However, he was released without ever being formally charged.

In 1951, Murata became a special advisor to the Foreign Ministry. He also appointed special ambassador to the Philippines in 1954, and worked towards normalization of relations and settlement of war-time compensation claims.  In the post-war period, Murata was president of the Japan Association for the Promotion of International Trade (JAPIT),<ref>{{cite book | last = Bauchamp | first = Edward | year = 2013 | title = Japan's Role in International Politics Since World War II| publisher = Routledge | isbn = 9781780939186}} page 158</ref> and a number of other charity associations. He also worked towards the restoration of [[diplomatic relations]] between China and Japan, visiting Beijing in 1952, and meeting with [[Zhou Enlai]] in 1955 in China and signing a trade agreement.<ref>{{cite book | last = Scalapino | first = Robert | year = 1977 | title = The Foreign Policy of Modern Japan| publisher = University of California Press | isbn = 0520034996 }} page 179</ref>

